lenders.loan_because:
The general complaint about globalization is that it has made the rich richer while making the non-rich poorer. It is wonderful for managers and investors, but hell on workers and nature. During the most recent period of rapid growth in global trade and investment, 1960 to 1998, inequality worsened both internationally and within countries. The UN Development Program reports that the richest 20% of the world's population consume 86% of the world's resources, while the poorest 80% consume just 14%. Social welfare schemes or “safety nets” are under great pressure in developed countries because of deficits and other economic ramifications of globalization. 

It's about general altruism, a personal hope to support an effective development tool, and social responsibility for people like me who are monetary well situated.
